text: Okay, the tape is now on, so I'll start out by asking you a little bit about your background and what in it might have led you to write science fiction. Oh, well now you've asked a double-barrel question there. Answer away. The second part derives out of the first, and maybe there's no connection in background in what led me to write science fiction. In the first place, my big brother, Billy. Oh, I've got to diverge a little bit here. That's fine. Have you read anything I've written? I've read everything you've written. Good God, I don't think I've done that myself. But, all right. My big brother is involved in various of my stories. The one which, the most recent, is the little paperback novel, The Catalyst. And he is one of the principal characters in there, although he is dead. And he comes back in a very spectacular way as a result of an incredible chemical experiment. Anyhow, my big brother, Billy, that was our family name for him. His real name was Blanford Bryan Hornet. And he was my idol. And he got all the amazing story magazines. He got Weird Tales from the drugstore, which I guess they don't publish anymore, but back in the middle 20s, they did. And Weird Tales had the original stories by Lovecraft. And I forget the name of the guy that writes Conan, but they had some of his short stories in it, too. And anyhow, he got me interested in it. I would borrow his copies surreptitiously and read them. Also, he had a few of the Edgar Rice Burroughs books, the Mars books, the first couple of Tarzan books, and so on. And these were remarkable things. I think A Princess of Mars is one of the best adventure stories ever written. And I've read it many times trying to analyze how Burroughs made certain of his points. It's beautifully paced, suspenseful. It develops instant sympathy with the characters and so on. Anyhow, that was a good one, and I read that. So I had read what there was to offer. Well, there were other stories, too. In Argosy, some of the Edgar Rice Burroughs stories were published as serials, like The Chestnut of Mars and other things by Burroughs and by other people, too. And my brother Billy also had H.G. Wells' books, The Time Machine, and I think it was called 30 Strange Stories. He had the Charles Fort books, Low and Book of the Damned, and so on. So I picked up a smattering of the stuff, and it was very exciting, and it was just a pleasure to read. I will mention here right away that one of my big disappointments in life was my trip to the Fort Worth Public Library. This was when I was 10 or 12 years old to see if I could find some of the books of Edgar Rice Burroughs. And nobody there had ever heard of him. So, well, I knew then that the world was divided into two kinds of people. And I might never meet friends of Edgar Rice Burroughs or of Tarzan or of John Carter or Deja Thoris in the Fort Worth Public Library. But I got other things there. Anyhow, that was the background. And my brother Billy was several years older than I. In fact, he was nine years older than I. And he died when I was just about to graduate from high school. He had tumors of the brain, which in those days were inoperable. Today, they don't, it wouldn't be too much trouble to operate if they couldn't do it then. So I have remembered him, and I have never let him go. And he has been in several of my stories. The Ring of Richard Nail. I don't know whether you've ever heard of that or not. Oh, yes. Anyhow, he was the brother who was destroyed by the chief bad guy. But his brain was retained. He was the poet. His name was Omer, which of course is taken from Homer, which is Greek for blind men. Anyhow, the two brothers were united at the end of the story. So that was sort of an idealized fantasy. Well, I had never written anything at all. I went through, well, I was working in Washington as a mineral economist during the war and going to law school. And my daughter was born in 1946, and there were some bills to be paid, and we needed the money. So I sat down and wrote my first science fiction story, which was Time Trip. And this was bought by what was then astounding. And I thought, well, gee, do they pay money for this stuff? So I thought perhaps I should turn out some more of it, which I did. So I wrote for a while until my daughter got old enough to demand more and more of my time. So the writing had to come to an end. And it didn't really resume again until she was ready to go off to college. This was in 1964. And I picked it up again. And I've been writing ever since. And that's a restart, as you might say. So that's the background of it. And I'm retired now. And I retired at the beginning of last year, January 4, 1982, the last day at work, when I've been writing a little bit off and on since then. And I have a few items out floating around with Scott Meredith, who is my agent at the moment. And here I am. May I call you, Bill? Please do. Okay. I'm Charlie. Thank you. Bill, I've been talking and talking and talking. And you've asked only one and a half questions. So the ratio of talk to questions is really getting out of hand. So try another question. Okay. What I want to do now is ask you some specific questions about your works and kind of see how they evolved. You wrote Time Trap, which was a story. And it had the time loops and the gradual awakening of a Superman, that sort of thing. And these elements were common in your later work. Were those themes something you picked up unconsciously, or was this something you were striving for in your work? Well, it must have been unconscious. This has been pointed out, or subconscious. I don't know which is the right word. This has been pointed out to me before. It's perhaps a mystical striving. And I don't know where it comes from. I did, or maybe you, yeah, you must have known. I did go to a ministerial school at TCU at one time. This was long, long ago. And they threw me out for reasons I won't go into here. But it was a wise decision. But I've never lost a mystic plant to lots of things. And not all of my stories have this supernatural inclination. Some are quite logical and down to earth. Some do, some don't. Have you read the Venetian court? Yes, I have. Well, now that's as down to earth as you can get. It has nothing. Well, I don't know. Maybe it has the computer. Yeah, he's not straight dialectic materialism. Well, who knows? I don't have a good answer to your question. No, that's fine. The fact that it is, and just as an aside, not part of the interview, that's, I think it's that mystical quality in your work which really appeals to me. Because later on, when we get into the Rose, that's where I really, really can go. But first, I want to bring up Flight Into Yesteryear, which was a novel. How did you decide to, I mean, you had tackled a short story and now all of a sudden you wrote a novel. Was that a pretty big decision to write a novel? Yeah, I needed a lot of money in a hurry. We had, I had finished law school, passed the D.C. bar, and got my first job as a patent attorney with American Cyanamid Company in Stanford, Connecticut. And housing was short. We were renting a little house up in Connecticut. And we were going to get evicted, it turned out. The lady wanted to sell her house. And we were looking around. We were desperate for a house. And it seemed to me the best way to scrape up the down payment for a house or else help get the money to rent one that I could afford would be to write a novel. So one thing led to another. And I sat down and in just about two months of weekend work, wrote the, you call it Flight Into Yesteryear. I'll get to that in a minute. That's not the right title. But anyhow, I wrote it very quickly, typed it up, got it over to Wonder Stories, which was in combination with Startling Stories, which was edited by Sam Mervin. And this was, let me see what year is this, 48, yes, 1948. About October 1, 1948. And a week later, he sent a check in the mail. Now, originally, it was 45,000 words, which is the length they wanted for a novel in one of their magazines. And then later on, it was expanded into a book. The original title, Bill, was nothing you've ever heard. It was Toynbee 22. Toynbee 22. After the ship? Yes. You have heard, of course, of the historian Toynbee, Arnold Toynbee. Yes. And his 21 civilizations, of which the Western, I think, is either the 20th or the 21st. And what's the next one after that? He doesn't say, but it would logically have to be the 22nd. So we're talking here about the next civilization, or fall of civilization, following the 21st, the Toynbee 21st civilization. So I call the little novel Toynbee 22. Merwin went through the roof. He said, nobody will understand Toynbee 22. Who's Toynbee? I renamed it to be Flight in the Yesterday. Of course, that does wrap up the time travel, traveling backwards angle. When it came out as a pocketbook later on, I believe, Wohlheim of Ace changed it to Paradox Man, with an explanation in the flyleaf of why everybody was a paradox, because he could never do what he wanted to or so on from. Which is okay. It was a teasing type of title, and I guess it stayed Paradox Man from then on out. So that's how it got the title. Now, what else about it? Okay, you apparently dashed this off in a couple of months, and yet the characters which really make the book are deeply drawn, and they're alive, and they're smart, and they're not really cardboard characters like so many of the science fiction characters of that era were. Where did you get this knack for developing the characters as you do? Oh, I lie a lot, Bill. I can see these guys, and I can project them, and I make up stories, and here they are as acting characters, and I can see their faces and the glints in their eyes and the curl, the sneery curl of their lips, if they're bad guys, or the sharp intake of breath when the hero sees a disaster looming. Actually, a lot of people, it's no big deal. But thank you for the compliment. Nobody's ever told me that they were other than cardboard characters. Oh, they definitely are. Okay, now this is where I have to get reverent, because The Rose came out, and The Rose, as far as I'm concerned, is the best science fiction book that was ever written. First thing I've got to ask you about it is, why did it appear, why was it first published in this obscure British magazine, Authentic? How did it ever end up there? Well, that's easy, because nobody here would buy it. My agent at the time, Forrest Ackerman of, I think, Los Angeles, peddled it around here and there. Nobody in this country would buy it. It went to John Camel, and he wrote a nice two-line letter bag. He just couldn't use it. It wasn't the kind of thing that any science fiction magazine or fantasy and science fiction magazine was publishing at the time. And I should have known better for writing it. But I wanted to write it, so I did. And finally, Ackerman sold it to this little authentic magazine in England, and they published it. And then after that, it began to get some circulation. Michael Moorcott picked it up for compact books. That's Sedgwick, I think. Something like that. But anyhow, they put out a little paperback. Then in England, it came out in a couple of hardcover editions. And then in this country, Berkeley, it may still be in front with Berkeley. I did a royalty check just last year. So it didn't come out here first because it's time it had not arrived. You had written before for money because you needed the money, and you wrote this one, you said, because you wanted to write it. What was it about this book that you wanted to write? Well, really, Jacques, again, resembles my brother a great deal. And if you can visualize that guy with his sarcasm, his biting wit, his contempt for all the... Well, I don't know, but he had a high personal integrity and an impatience with convention and so on. At least in his head, he did. And I wanted to get him in the print. And, of course, Anna Van Tau is me, although I tried to take on a female form to make it effective. I would have... At one time, I would have been pleased to die if it would bring him back. But, of course, that was just being said. But it was a thought, and it was a psychic force driving the story. You talked at length in this book about the enmity between science and art. Is that something that you feel exists or has existed before? Oh, I suppose so. It's not a big thing, Bill. But there is always a question. What... Take a university. They have a budget. Does it go into the physics department, your department, the chemistry department, or will they establish a chair for teaching the Renaissance in Italy or the old masters, the painters? Will they have a music school? Or how does... Where does it get divided up? There is a conflict. At the time I wrote that, I think there was a bigger conflict than there is now. I think science was one, at least temporarily. Thirty years ago, it wasn't at all clear. That was not too clear. The ending of that book was very moving. It was not a tearjerker. It was very realistically portrayed. Did you have that ending, I'm curious, in mind, when you wrote it, or did that just develop and that's how it turned out? It just developed. That was... I did not... That was one of the stories where I didn't know how it was going to come out. And in fact, I worked on that one for two years, Bill. This is not a two-month job. I read all the books on the arts in the Stanford Public Library. This is one year. I took notes on them for my entire two weeks vacation one year. And then it gradually began to come together. And I used, of course, as you've seen in the story, Oscar Wilde's story of The Nightingale and the Rose, which I'd read many years before and I was quite impressed by it. So, the ending, though, yeah, I worked on that. At one time, it had other endings. But I can't remember what they were. This is the best ending, I think. Oh, yeah. Again, it had that element of this transcendental experience, which kind of led one to suspect there might be a race of supermen that were going to be forming. Well, that was the idea. With this power that he had, he would then be able to do all kinds of wonderful things. And it was given to him by this act of love at the end. The British critics, Arthur C. Clarke and Judith Merrill, Michael Moorcock, Brian Oldis, really liked The Rose. And yet, it seemed that it was another decade or so before it ever caught on over here. Do you have any pet theories on why in England it was a success, but not one over here particularly at first? Well, I think this is due to the efforts of Michael Moorcock. He launched it over there and then it was picked up over here. Let me give you a little bit more history on this. There was a time when The Rose was in a longer form and it had the name not The Rose but Invitation. It was an intergalactic thing where the Earth was being examined to see whether it would be admitted into a galactic brotherhood and it didn't have the ending that it now has. Damon Knight liked that but he couldn't get his publishers to accept it. This again was a year or so before it came out and it's inauthentic in its short form which tells nothing. So at that point I said maybe I'm going to shorten this thing down give it a different ending so I did. I cut it from 45,000 words down to I think it's about 30,000 now. And it Ackerman then was able to sell it to Authentic in England. And then it began to pick up Arthur Clark saw it Arthur Moorcock saw it and Moorcock was getting into the editor business over there at that time asked to have his people compact books publish it and we have a contract for that and they did publish it. Then it was picked up fairly quickly by two other British outfits and hardcover for them and of course they had to pad it out with the two other stories to make it in a book size. And Damon Knight then picked it up from the British. He said, hey, here's the thing I've been thinking about all these many years and that's come out in Britain. Why didn't you give it to me? He said, okay. I sold Berkeley the rights, the U.S. rights to it. And that's why all the time lags. If it hadn't been from Moorcock it would never have gone anywhere. There or here. It was interesting though that it was it appeared in England and then it was 13 years later that Berkeley finally put it out as the paperback and that's the only American printing. It came out let's see, 1953 I believe in authentic then about another 10 years in pocketbook form paperback and another couple of years over here. Yeah. Yeah, well a prophet is not not without honor save in his own country. I was not the first to say that. That's the my theory on it was always that the new wave started in England and maybe they were more attuned to the kind of writing. You got a point there. They could live with something like this whereas over here everybody was guided pretty much by the dean of science fiction John Camel and he was a hardware man and everything had to obey the laws of physics or it would be unacceptable. But I've written many good things for him and I'm grateful that he bought my first story so I can't complain about John Camel. Great guy. Now the invitation has never been published as such right? Correct. Good because I couldn't say I'd read everything if it had. Well one or two other little items you haven't read either but they're submerged and now we're dragging up now. Well I'll get on to them but if you're talking about Leonard Lockhart or whatever I read them the two anyway. Oh well that was a collaborative effort you know. I guess this would be as good a time as any to ask about the Leonard Lockhart stories. Was it Ted Thomas? Who was it? Yeah. Okay. Ted and I we were in the patent department at Sinamed together. I wrote the first Leonard Lockhart story Improbable Profession and at that time he was writing science articles for the Stanford Advocate as well as being on the patent in the patent department at Sinamed. So I said to him why don't you and I start this series of stories about a patent attorney and his problems. Here's the first one. So he said yeah we can do that. So I wrote the first one he wrote the second one. No together we wrote the second one. It was half and half. And after that I left Sinamed and went to Grace and he continued the series. So number three is an all subsequent stories or his even though the name Leonard Lockhart is still used on him. Okay that'll be a good bridge to the question after this one. But this question is in 1953 then we saw two short stories, Child Book Chronos and the chess players. And then you disappeared for 13 years. How did you, what happened? You wrote for this five years pretty intensively and then zapped you're gone for a while. How did you decide to do that? Well, as I mentioned Bill, my little girl was growing up and at that time I was riding up in the attic of the house I was renting and later on the one of that bought. And she would stand down in the hallway and cry. She wanted me to come down and play with her, which I did. And I put my riding aside and I said, well, first things first, let's bring up this little girl, raise her right, give her some attention, and if there's time left over to write, I might do some riding. But there was never any time left over. And I got out of the habit altogether until she went off to college. And I thought, gee, I'm going to need some tuition money here, so I better get back with this stuff, which I did. So it was money again that made you start up. Yeah. Okay, when you, I'm sorry, go ahead. I'm not sure right now whether I'm doing it for money or just to see if I can still do it. I'm curious as to whether I've lost the touch, and maybe this year I will find out. Anyhow, right now I'm not doing it for money, although the money would be nice. So there are motives for you. Why do people write? Go ahead, Bill. You had a question? Okay. In 1966, then, or approximately then, whenever you did start up, all of a sudden we're seeing a different kind of story, the lawyer stories. and I've got an ornament to his profession and the alchemist, which were kind of related because they were both at the same chemical company, and then the million-year patent and probable cause, but they're all law stories. So I've already asked you why you started writing. That was my first question. And why did you switch to this kind of story, which was so different from the other stuff except for the Leonard Lockhart stories? Well, I thought maybe I should use something, I knew something about. This is my field, my professional field, patent work in law, and goodness knows there's plenty of drama in it, so I thought maybe I should use some of this local history as background. And of course that showed up profoundly in the catalyst, and later on in the Venetian court. So it's something I know and I thought I would try it out. But then you wrote these stories, but then you kept it off with the Ring of Ritternell, which was kind of a throwback to the old style. Well, that well, let me, yeah, okay. That was kind of a throwback. That was an intermediate thing. I can't explain the anomaly there, Bill. Well, it was a wonderful anomaly, if it was an anomaly. If it was an anomaly, it was a good one. Well, thank you. The interesting thing, the mystical part here to me was you had the two different religions vying for each other, one of them essentially saying that blind chance rules the universe, and the other one saying that it's guided by something. And it seemed to me that you ended up by kind of siding with the latter, that there is something guiding the cosmos. And that was a really philosophical book. And the thing there, too, the invention, the deep, where was it Omer that stayed there for 18 years in the deep? And I'd seen evidence of that earlier, this kind of blind space where the protagonist goes and is disembodied and then comes back. Does that have any special meaning to you, or is that out of your subconscious? It isn't Omer that went into the deep. He was the brother, whose brain was expressed. Okay, right. I'm getting it mixed up. But, okay, I'm sorry, I interrupted you. Oh, no, we might as well get it right here. Yeah, the deep, where did that come up? Because I'd seen evidence for that before in some of the earlier stories from the decade earlier. I thought that would be a very impressive concept of some all-encompassing milieu, as it were, where only the consciousness can exist. And this is the use that I put it to. But beyond that, Bill, I just can't really remember. The concept of a mind wandering in the deep does go way, way back, and I had it many years before that. I just didn't have a chance to use it. Okay, you had done a lot of homework on this novel, too, as far as you used the steady-state cosmology theory so that the universe is continually being made up again and being recreated. Yeah, well, of course, that's one of the standard theories. I think that's gradually yielding now, though. Right, but it made it interesting. It allowed you to have this rebirth, which you tend to do, the transcendental rebirth, and it fit really nicely with steady-state cosmology. Yeah. But on that very point, I don't know whether you've read Firebird. Oh, yes. Now, that one starts out with a big bang and expands and then stops and contracts. So we have an oscillation. and there are an infinite number of big bangs because when it contracts, it goes back into the original Fireball and it goes up and expands again. So that's another theory. That's the apotheosis of the big bang theory. Yeah, it's the big bang with the closed universe option where you have enough mass to make it oscillate. Yeah. Okay, you wrote The Ring of Riturnal and then, that was 1968, then you disappeared for another six years until The Arachnid Window came out. What caused this interlude, if I may ask? Oh, let me think there. Gee, did I stop? I can't recall. I must have stopped. Or at least you didn't appear in print for six years. I'm trying to think. Oh, my daughter graduated. She graduated in 68. And the heat was off real long. And I had to get back on with my son. He started again in 72. And it continued for quite a while. but I just didn't realize there was that gap. Maybe I was just goofing off. Well, we missed you. The Arachnid Window, when you did get back in again, I really enjoyed that story and it has the time loop. But I think the thing I enjoyed about that story more than anything was the professor, who was obviously in the twilight of his career, kind of looking back and wondering if it was all worth it and that sort of thing. I liked his point of view. Well, I'm glad you liked it. About that time, I realized I was someday soon going to have to retire from grace. So I put myself in it a little bit. But again, it was a mishmash. time It uses a number of things that were, well, each incident probably has some counterpart in some previous science fiction story. Time travel, of course, is one of the most patented themes possible. But time survival, which is what happened here, might be a little different. And some of the technology there is purely invented. Okay, all of a sudden, you had four novels that came out. Bang, bang, bang, bang. And Wolfhead was the first one, and it was quite different from anything, to me, anyway, than anything you'd written before. How long had you thought about it? How did it come up? Oh, I consider that one sort of a potboiler, Bill. I started out writing it, I thought I would do a thing which is frowned upon. You're not supposed to write post-atomic novels. It's, they're really unacceptable. But here seemed to be a good one. And I hope you're not a pro Nixon fan. No, not at all. Well, I thought, gee, here's this guy, he's about to take over the country. Anything he does is okay just because he says so. And I'm going to have a character like that in Wolfhead. So I put him in there. He was the president of the underworld. And he would come out and rule the upper world. Except he didn't. The wolf was modeled at the time on an Alaskan husky dog that lived next door to us. And she and I were great friends. So I thought I'd put her in it. And one thing led to another and it all seemed to come together. And of course you've got to have telepathy and a thing like that. There were certain novel aspects of it though like absorbing the energy of the potential earthquake into a gigantic spinning sphere and that in turn generating the power to create a vortex in those that have the power. So there were some novel features and it's one of my happier efforts. It's not really serious. well some of it is. You know at one time it had a different ending and I have to cough when I think about it. Excuse me while I cough. This is a psychological cough. That was a psychological cough. in the original ending the girl lived but I got involved in some chemical litigation that I lost and I was so angry and so disappointed I said somebody has to die. So I killed the heroine and wrote some poetry for her benefit so she wouldn't feel too badly about it. And that the poetry of course is in the front and in the back. So that's a little sidelight on that. I never would have guessed that. You thought everything came out logically. You thought it in advance. Our personal lives control a lot of what we do. I've got what I have. I have about five more questions but I have to flip my tape in a minute. You mentioned the device, the novelty in that and I meant to mention earlier the device in the Paradox Men or the body shield with which bullets would not pierce but low momentum projectiles would with the swords. I really have always liked that device as a novelty in science fiction. Well, I needed something like that to get in some sword play. Why would you want to have sword play when you can just pull out a pistol and shoot a guy in the gut? Well, the only way you can do it is if a pistol doesn't work. So then you've got to have something that goes in a little floor and can secure him properly. And therefore, you will need some kind of shield such as that. So that's the way I figured it anyhow. Okay. I'm glad I had remembered to ask that question here. Tell you, let me change my tape. It'll take about two minutes and I only have about five more questions if you can hang in there. Yeah, go ahead, Bill. Okay, thank you. If you want to take a break or something, just put the phone down and we'll holler at you. Get a drink of water and come back and wait for your sounds good. Okay.
